<DOC><DOCNO> AP890312-0047 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-89 1614EST</FILEID><FIRST>r p AM-Koch-Popularity     03-12 0353</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Koch-Popularity,0364</SECOND><HEAD>Poll: Koch Popularity Hits New Low, Giuliani in Lead</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Mayor Edward I. Koch, his popularity at a newlow, would lose at every level of a mayoral election, and formerU.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani would win, according to a pollreleased Sunday.   Among Democrats, Manhattan Borough President David Dinkins wouldbeat Koch in a primary if it were being held now, according to thepoll. The primary is set for September and the general election forNovember.   The telephone poll, conducted March 3-7 by the GallupOrganization for New York Newsday, surveyed 1,012 New Yorkers.   Six months before the primary, 50 percent of those polleddisapproved of how the three-term mayor does his job, up five pointsin three months. Thirty-one percent approved of the mayor'sperformance, down from 37 percent in December.   Sunday's poll showed Dinkins leading a four-way Democraticprimary against Koch, Comptroller Harrison J. Goldin and real estatedeveloper Richard Ravitch. In the runoff poll, Dinkins would beatKoch, 58 percent to 32 percent; and Goldin, 54 percent to 26 percent.   Asked how they would vote in the November general election,respondents chose Republican Giuliani, the popular former prosecutorwho has not announced his candidacy but has indicated an interest inrunning, over Koch or Dinkins.   Giuliani beat either Koch or Dinkins one-on-one, and both in athree-way general election. Voters preferred Giuliani to Koch, 58percent to 31 percent, and to Dinkins, 48 percent to 41 percent.   The only declared Republican candidate, Former Ambassador RonaldLauder, son of cosmetics tycoon Estee Lauder, was not included inthe poll.   In every ethnic division except Hispanics, Koch met with moredisapproval than approval. Koch, asked to respond, said, ``there'snothing surprising in the poll.''   Giuliani saw the numbers as ``encouraging, and they're areflection of support I've been getting when I walk along thestreets.''   The poll's margin of error was plus or minus 6 percent. NoDemocrat candidate got the 40 percent needed to avert a runoffbetween the top two candidates. Dinkins had 37 percent, Koch 28percent, and Ravitch 4 percent.</TEXT></DOC>